<td tEditID="c1r1" style=" background-color:#FFFFFF; bEditID:r3st1; color:#000000; bLabel:main; font-size:12pt; font-family:arial;" aEditID="c1r1" locked="0" >
<![CDATA[<div style="text-align: right;"><div style=""><div style="text-align: left;"><div style=""><div style=""><div style=""><div style=""><div style=""><div style=""><div style=""><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Dear Parents,&nbsp;</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">The health and safety of your children is our top priority. In addition to taking all necessary precautions, we aim to always keep our parents well informed of health issues that come to our attention. This letter is being sent to inform you that there has recently been confirmed case of Whooping Cough in Year 10.</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Overview</b></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Whooping cough is a contagious bacterial infection of the lungs and airway that most commonly affects young children. It is spread in the droplets of coughs or sneezes of someone who is affected. This illness can be particularly severe in babies and infants.</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Symptoms</b></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">The first symptoms of whooping cough are similar to those of a cold, such as a runny nose, red and watery eyes, a sore throat and a slightly raised temperature. More intense coughing bouts start about a week later. Coughing usually brings up thick mucus and may be followed by vomiting. The child may also experience difficulty breathing and should be carefully monitored.</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Please seek immediate medical advice and advise the school promptly if your child is unwell with any of the above symptoms.</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>School Precautions</b></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">At school, we are taking all precautions necessary including:&nbsp;</font></div><div style=""><ul><li><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Implementing good hygiene measures.</font></li><li><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Daily cleaning and disinfection of surfaces, door handles, stair railings, toys, bathroom accessories and food utensils.</font></li><li><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Unwell children will see a nurse and parents will be contacted, if necessary.</font></li><li><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Children have been taught how to wash their hands by teachers and also how to cover their mouths and noses when coughing or sneezing.</font></li></ul></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">If you believe your child has whooping cough, please seek medical treatment, follow safety procedures at home and keep them away from school until they have recovered from the illness. Please keep us informed of any cases that are confirmed by a doctor.</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Vaccinations</b></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">There are several vaccines that can protect babies and young children from whooping cough. These do not offer lifelong protection, but can protect children for several years when they are young and more vulnerable. If you are interested in your child being vaccinated, please consult directly with your doctor.</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">For further information about whooping cough, please see the link below:&nbsp;</font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><a href="http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Whooping-cough/">http://www.nhs.uk/Conditions/Whooping-cough/</a></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><br></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Warm Regards,</font></div><div style=""><br></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2"><b>Dean Moore</b></font></div><div style=""><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">Head of Upper Campus and Secondary School</font></div><div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: 12pt;"><br></div></div><div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: arial; font-size: 12pt;"><font face="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2" style=""><div style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);">Sent Via Admissions Office</div></font></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div></div>]]></td>
